{{Infobox royalty | name = Archaeanax | title = Ruler of the Bosporan Kingdom | image = | image_size = 250px | caption = | reign = 480-? BC | native_lang1 = Greek | native_lang1_name1 = {{lang|grc|Αρχαιάναξ}} | birth_date = | birth_place = Mytilene | death_date =470 BC? | death_place = Bosporan Kingdom | predecessor = ''Position Established'' | successor = ? | queen = | royal house = [[Archaeanactids]] | father = Unknown | mother = Unknown | issue = | place of burial = | religion = [[Religion in ancient Greece|Greek Polytheism]] }}
'''Archaeanax''' ([[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: Αρχαιάναξ) seems to have been a ruler of the [[Bosporan Kingdom]] some 40 years prior to the ascent of the Thracian [[Spartocids]].
==Biography== Little to nothing is known about Archaeanax prior to his ascent to the throne. He may have been a native of [[Mytilene]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Minns|title=Scythians and Greeks: A Survey of Ancient History and Archaeology |url=https://books.google.com.do/books?id=ijJ4o2iorhkC&pg=PA570&lpg=PA570&dq=archaenax&source=bl&ots=Pi2ziUPpml&sig=fgnPCtGWg4ProzsdAIBZJinpZgY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjC1eWf2vPVAhXIwFQKHR_bCD4Q6AEIKzAA#v=onepage&q=archaenax&f=false|quote=bringing them into connexion with Archaeanax of Mytilene}}</ref> and a ''strategos'' of a league of city-states in the Cimmerian Bosporus<ref>{{cite book|last=Podossinov|first=Alexander|title=Encyclopaedia of the Hellenic World|url=http://blacksea.ehw.gr/forms/fLemmaBodyExtended.aspx?lemmaID=10766|quote=Archaeanaktus could have been a strategos of the already mentioned league that turned it into a tyranny}}</ref> that likely formed as a defense of the neighboring Scythian tribes. After taking power as ruler, the cities of the Theodosia and Nymphaeum left the league.<ref>{{cite book|last=Podossinov|first=Alexander|title=Encyclopaedia of the Hellenic World|url=http://blacksea.ehw.gr/forms/fLemmaBodyExtended.aspx?lemmaID=10766|quote=It is possible that the Crimean cities of Nymphaeum and Theodosia left the league during the establishment of the tyranny}}</ref> It is possible that he was related to Semandrus of Mytilene, founder of the city of [[Hermonassa]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Podossinov|first=Alexander|title=Encyclopaedia of the Hellenic World|url=http://blacksea.ehw.gr/forms/fLemmaBodyExtended.aspx?lemmaID=10766|quote=where the Greek city of Hermonassa, founded by Semandrus from Mitylene}}</ref> though this is uncertain.
