'''Operation Auxin''' was an Australian police operation in September 2004, leading to the [[arrest]] of almost 200 people on charges of [[child pornography]]. These people were all accused of purchasing child pornography over the [[Internet]], using their [[credit card]]s, from [[Belarus]]ian [[Organized crime|crime syndicates]], the credit card payments having been processed by a company named Landslide.com in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida|Fort Lauderdale]], [[Florida]]. Among the accused were people holding positions of trust in the community, such as [[police officer]]s (including one  officer assigned to investigate child pornography), members of the military, [[teacher]]s and [[minister of religion|minister]]s of religion. Several of the suspects committed [[suicide]]. It was the follow-up to the U.S. [[FBI]] operation [[Operation Falcon (child pornography crackdown)|Operation Falcon]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Operation Auxin explained|url=http://www.smh.com.au/media/2004/09/30/1096527872004.html|website=Sydney Morning Herald|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090211143041/http://www.smh.com.au/media/2004/09/30/1096527872004.html|archivedate=11 February 2009}}</ref>

The initial credit card evidence used in the investigation has since been widely debunked due to there being no established link between a credit card being used and actual pornography being downloaded.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Campbell|first1=Duncan|title=Operation Ore flawed by fraud|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2007/apr/19/hitechcrime.money|website=The Guardian|date=19 April 2007}}</ref> Additionally, multiple cases of [[credit card fraud]] involving organised crime syndicates has also raised the possibility that credit card numbers retrieved from Landslide.com may have been used by a third party and not their owners at all.<ref name=alphr>{{cite web|last1=Campbell|first1=Duncan|title=Operation Ore exposed|url=http://www.alphr.com/features/74690/operation-ore-exposed|website=Alphr|date=1 July 2005}}</ref>

Similar operations in the UK have come under intense fire both from those wrongfully convicted and from civil rights groups.<ref name=alphr/>

